  <h2 id="how-it-works">How Air Ambulance Coverage Works</h2>

  <h3>The Process</h3>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Emergency occurs:</strong> You call the 24/7 assistance line</li>
    <li><strong>Medical assessment:</strong> Team evaluates if air transport is medically necessary</li>
    <li><strong>Coordination:</strong> They arrange aircraft, medical team, receiving hospital</li>
    <li><strong>Transport:</strong> You're transported with medical care en route</li>
    <li><strong>Arrival:</strong> Ground ambulance meets you, transfers to hospital</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Key Considerations</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Medical necessity:</strong> Air ambulance must be medically required, not just convenient</li>
    <li><strong>Pre-authorization:</strong> Usually required except in life-threatening emergencies</li>
    <li><strong>Destination:</strong> Usually to nearest adequate facility, not necessarily home</li>
    <li><strong>Timing:</strong> Weather, aircraft availability, and logistics affect timing</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Limits and Exclusions</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Some plans have dollar limits ($100K-500K)</li>
    <li>Premium plans often have unlimited coverage</li>
    <li>Pre-existing conditions may affect coverage</li>
    <li>War zones and certain countries may be excluded</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="faqs">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <h3>How much does an air ambulance cost without insurance?</h3>
  <p>
    Air ambulance flights cost $15,000-150,000+ depending on distance, aircraft type, and medical needs. International medical evacuations can exceed $100,000. Helicopter evacuations from remote areas cost $10,000-50,000+.
  </p>

  <h3>Is air ambulance covered by all international health insurance?</h3>
  <p>
    Most full international health insurance plans include air ambulance. Coverage limits vary—some offer unlimited, others cap at $100K-500K. Budget travel medical plans typically include it but with lower limits. Always verify coverage limits.
  </p>

  <h3>What triggers air ambulance coverage?</h3>
  <p>
    Air ambulance must be medically necessary. Triggers include: no adequate local medical care, need for specialist treatment unavailable locally, remote location requiring helicopter access, or critical condition requiring rapid transport. Convenience alone doesn't qualify.
  </p>

  <h3>Can I choose where I'm evacuated to?</h3>
  <p>
    Usually you're evacuated to the nearest adequate medical facility, not necessarily your preferred location. Repatriation to home country typically happens once you're stable, if medically appropriate. Some premium plans offer more flexibility.
  </p>

  <h3>Does air ambulance include family members?</h3>
  <p>
    Premium plans often include coverage for a family member to travel to your bedside. This typically covers economy flights, not the air ambulance itself. Check your specific plan for family travel benefits.
  </p>

  <h3>Is helicopter evacuation the same as air ambulance?</h3>
  <p>
    Helicopter evacuation is a type of air ambulance service, typically used for shorter distances or accessing remote locations. Fixed-wing air ambulances (planes) are used for longer distances. Both are usually covered under air ambulance benefits.
  </p>

